"Co-owned the Granite Mills in Talcottville at the time of the 1881 fire.","link_text":"Anson F. Talcott"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Built the Granite Mills","body":"Samuel Smith Talcott founded the Granite Mills on the lower Hockanum River in Talcottville, establishing a linseed oil operation around 1838 that was converted to paper manufacturing after an 1863 fire. The mill purchased old paper in bales from New York, Boston, and Philadelphia, recycling it into binder boards, album covers, and press paper — running day and night, producing up to 25 tons a week. His middle name \"Smith\" honored his mother Sarah Smith; his mills neighbored, but were entirely separate from, the Talcottville mill of his distant cousins."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"The mill burned four times","body":"The Granite Mills were destroyed by fire in 1863, 1870, and 1881, rebuilt each time. After the 1870 fire the Tolland County Journal noted \"there is enterprise enough remaining there to rebuild.\" The final fire came August 1, 1912 — started by spontaneous combustion in 75 tons of waste paper. The mill was not rebuilt."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Talcott Pedigree 1876"},{"label":"Tankerhoosen Valley History — Granite Mills","url":"https://www.tankerhoosen.info/history/mill_granite.htm"},{"label":"Tolland County Journal, Feb 12, 1870 (fire account)"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Samuel","middle_name":"Smith","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"display_name":"Samuel Smith Talcott"},"military_service":[],"slug":"samuel-talcott-1793"},"T01193":{"id":"T01193","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":true,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1819,"month":4,"day":26,"city":"Vernon","county":"Tolland","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1824,"month":1,"day":1,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{},"resid